Lamiae pietas et eura ‘Lamia's love and trouble’: this cannot mean, as some have taken it, ‘my love for Lamia’ z pictas seems never to be used with an objective genitive, and it is doubtful whether it could denote an affection not based upon any natural ties, such as exist in the case of parents or kinsmen. L. Aelius Lamia is the man to whom Carm. 111. 17 is addressed, and who is also mentioned in Carm. Ι. 26, 8. Η6 was of a noble and wealthy plebeian family (cp. Juv. IV. 154, VI. 384, Tac. Ann. Vl. 27), and attained the consulship in A.D. 3. He held high office under Tiberius, and was honoured with a public funeral when he died in A.D. 33. The name of Q. Aeiius Lamia occurs on a coin of this date, and this appears to be the brother here referred to. Lucius must have been the elder brother, as he bore his father's praenomen, but he must himself have been young at this time, sor we cannot date this epistle less than about fifty-five years before his death, and as he was appointed p1·‹z<y‘i·cszts maz* in A.D. 32 he cannot have attained extreme old age, though Tacitus speaks of his vivida seneclus. 7. maerentis—dolentis: the assonance is doubtless acci- (lentalz cp. note on Ep. 1. 12, 25. Macreo is to express grief, doleo is to feel it: cp. Cic. ad Att. XII. 28, 2 maerorem minui, dolorem nec potui, uec, si possem, vellem.
